---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why isn't a 150mm stump grind deep enough before paving on a Central Coast block?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A 150mm grind is the lawn-only depth — it lets you re-turf or drop in a couple of inches of topsoil and forget the stump exists. Pavers, a concrete slab or strip footings are a different problem. Pavers are usually bedded on 50–80mm of road base over a 100mm compacted sub-base, which already eats your 150mm before you've laid the first paver. Worse, any remaining stump shoulder sits in the wet zone under the paving and rots over the next 18–36 months, leaving a soft pocket that drops your pavers visibly. From the Wamberal sand-belt down through Erina and inland to Lisarow we grind to 600mm under any future paving, slab or footing and chase the four cardinal lateral roots out past the future edge of the build." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does a 600mm grind cost extra over a standard stump grind?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "On a single Central Coast stump of 400–700mm diameter, the extra to drop the grind from a standard 200–300mm down to a clean 600mm is typically $80–$220 on top of the base grind price. The reason it isn't double is the machine is already on site, the operator is already running it, and only the bottom 300mm is genuinely new work. If you have multiple stumps the per-stump premium drops further. We'd rather you ring once and pay the extra now than have us back in a year because your pavers are dipping." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What should the root-zone be backfilled with before building over a ground stump?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Not the wood chip. Wood chip rots, loses 30–60% of its volume in the first two summers, and gives you a settle hole exactly where you don't want one. For anything load-bearing we remove the chip, then backfill the void in 150mm lifts of road base or 20mm crushed rock, compacting each lift with a plate compactor. The top 100mm can be sand or sandy loam if you're paving direct, or a structural fill spec if a slab is going over. We'll dump the chip on your garden bed as mulch — it's still useful, just not as footing-grade fill." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long should I wait before pouring concrete or laying pavers over a ground stump?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "If the void is backfilled with compacted road base in 150mm lifts as above, you can build over it the same week. If the hole is filled with the wood chip from the grind, you need to wait 18–24 months for the chip to break down and settle, and even then you'll usually still get some subsidence. Most Central Coast owners don't have 18 months. So the rule is: backfill structurally, build that month. Backfill with chip, only ever turf or plant on top of it." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Stump Grinding Depth Central Coast — Pre-Paving & Pre-Footing"
  description="600mm stump grinding on the Central Coast for owners about to pave, slab or build. Why a lawn-grade 150mm grind isn't enough, the structural backfill spec, and the settle window before you build over it."
  canonical="https://centralcoasttreeservice.com.au/stump-grinding-central-coast/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Pre-paving &middot; pre-footing &middot; AQF-qualified arborists</span>
      <h1>Stump grinding depth on the <span class="accent">Central Coast</span> — when 150mm isn&rsquo;t enough.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        If you&rsquo;re paving, pouring a slab, dropping in strip footings or laying a
        permanent path over a ground stump, the lawn-grade 150mm grind your last quote
        was based on will fail you inside 18 months. We grind to 600mm under any future
        build, chase the lateral roots out past the build edge, and give you a
        compaction-grade backfill spec so you don&rsquo;t end up with a paver dip or a
        slab crack where the stump used to be.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/quote/">Get a 600mm grind quote</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="tel:+61485939966">Call us</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The Central Coast soil profile makes this worse, not better</h2>
      <p>
        From Killcare and Umina across the Woy Woy peninsula, through the sandy
        sediment around Wamberal and Terrigal, and the heavier clays of Lisarow,
        Wyong and out to the Tuggerah Lakes catchment, the Central Coast doesn&rsquo;t
        give you a forgiving sub-grade. Sandy blocks let the rotting stump column
        drain wet and dry repeatedly, accelerating breakdown of any remaining wood
        and pulling fines down into the void. Clay blocks shrink and swell with
        every wet/dry cycle and lift any uncompacted fill out of true. Either way,
        if you grind shallow and build over it, the build moves.
      </p>
      <p>
        We&rsquo;ve been called back to too many Avoca Beach courtyards and Erina
        Heights driveways where a $300 lawn-grade grind was done two summers ago
        and now there&rsquo;s a 40&ndash;80mm dip under the pavers. The grinder cost
        was identical &mdash; the cheap job missed the lateral roots and stopped
        at 200mm. The fix is to lift the pavers, re-grind, re-base, re-lay. Cheaper
        to do once, properly.
      </p>

      <h2>The 600mm rule and what it actually means</h2>
      <p>
        Six hundred millimetres below finished surface level is the depth we work
        to for any future paving, slab, strip footing, retaining-wall footing or
        permanent path. It&rsquo;s deeper than most homeowners expect because the
        sum of the build-up is bigger than they expect: 150mm of road base, 30mm
        of bedding sand, 60mm of paver, plus the original turf and topsoil you&rsquo;ve
        already scraped off, and you&rsquo;re routinely 250&ndash;350mm down before
        you even touch the stump shoulder. Add the rooting depth of the four
        cardinal laterals from a mature stump and 600mm is the honest number.
      </p>
      <p>
        AQF Level 3 is the working-arborist trade qualification we hold &mdash;
        the certificate that says we&rsquo;re trained to operate a stump grinder
        and read a root collar. AQF Level 5 is the consulting tier (the one you
        engage for AS 4970 tree-protection reports or risk assessments to court
        standard). For a stump grind to depth, AQF 3 is the qualification you&rsquo;re
        paying for, and you should ask to see it. A landscaper with a hired
        grinder is not an arborist.
      </p>

      <h2>The backfill spec we leave you with</h2>
      <p>
        When the grind&rsquo;s done we don&rsquo;t just dump the chip back in and
        wave goodbye. For a build-grade finish we extract the chip from the void,
        leave it in a heap on your garden bed if you want mulch (it&rsquo;s genuinely
        good mulch &mdash; eucalypt fines, slightly aged), and then either backfill
        with road base in 150mm lifts compacted with a plate, or hand the void
        over to your concreter / paver / builder for them to backfill to their
        own spec. Most of the better Central Coast paving crews want to base-it
        themselves so the warranty stays clean. We&rsquo;ll work to whatever your
        next trade wants &mdash; just tell us at the quote.
      </p>
      <p>
        Typical removal-plus-grind pricing across the region for a single mature
        tree (12&ndash;18m, common species like spotted gum, angophora, jacaranda,
        camphor laurel) is $300 at the easy end (small tree, drop and chip, single
        stump grind to lawn depth) up to $1,500 for big jobs (tight access, crane
        not required, multiple stumps, 600mm grind on the main stump). Storm-damage
        callouts and craned removals quote separately.
      </p>

      <h2>Settle window &mdash; how long before you build over it</h2>
      <p>
        With a road-base structural backfill compacted in lifts: the next trade can
        start the same week. With a wood-chip backfill: 18&ndash;24 months minimum,
        and most owners still see 30&ndash;60mm of subsidence at the centre of the
        chip column even then. The chip breaks down and the void re-opens. So if
        the brief is &ldquo;build over it&rdquo;, the brief on the day of the grind
        is &ldquo;chip out, road base in&rdquo;. If the brief is &ldquo;new garden bed
        over it&rdquo;, the chip can stay &mdash; it&rsquo;ll just settle into a
        dished bed and you&rsquo;ll top it up with topsoil twice over the next
        couple of years.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>FAQs &mdash; depth, cost, fill, settle window</h2>
      <h3>Why isn&rsquo;t a 150mm stump grind deep enough before paving?</h3>
      <p>
        The paver build-up (sub-base, bedding sand, paver) eats your 150mm before
        the first paver lands. Anything left of the stump shoulder rots into a
        soft pocket within 18&ndash;36 months and your pavers visibly drop. Anywhere
        from Wamberal to Lisarow we grind to 600mm under future paving, slab or
        footing and chase the four cardinal laterals out past the edge.
      </p>
      <h3>What&rsquo;s the extra cost to go from a 200mm grind to a 600mm grind?</h3>
      <p>
        Usually $80&ndash;$220 on a single 400&ndash;700mm stump on top of the base
        grind. The machine&rsquo;s already on site, the operator&rsquo;s already
        running it, so only the bottom 300mm is genuinely new work. Multiple
        stumps drop the premium further per stump.
      </p>
      <h3>What do you backfill the void with before building over it?</h3>
      <p>
        Not the wood chip &mdash; chip rots and loses 30&ndash;60% of its volume,
        giving you a settle hole. For anything load-bearing we remove the chip
        and backfill in 150mm lifts of road base or 20mm crushed rock, plate-compacted.
        The chip goes on your garden bed as free mulch.
      </p>
      <h3>How long after the grind before I can pour the slab or lay the pavers?</h3>
      <p>
        Same week, if backfill is compacted road base. 18&ndash;24 months, if backfill
        is the wood chip from the grind &mdash; and you&rsquo;ll still likely see
        subsidence. So the rule is structural backfill &rarr; build now; chip backfill
        &rarr; turf or plant only.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner cta-block">
      <h2>Booking a grind before your concreter, paver or builder shows up?</h2>
      <p>
        Tell us at the quote &mdash; we&rsquo;ll work to the depth your next trade
        needs, give you a written backfill spec they can sign off, and time the
        grind so the void isn&rsquo;t open through a wet weekend. AQF Level 3
        qualified, SafeWork NSW licensed, fully insured, and we work the full
        coast from Killcare to Lake Macquarie&rsquo;s edge.
      </p>
      <p class="ph-text">
        Call <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61485939966">+61 485 939 966</a>
        or email <a href="mailto:quotes@centralcoasttreeservice.com.au">quotes@centralcoasttreeservice.com.au</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
